<center>She hurried through one place after another, already somewhat exhausted. She was on the verge of slipping out of this world, and the only thing she could do was run down the path called self-rescue.</center>


<center>Her mind raced wildly, trying to understand how everything had ended up like this. Her mouth was unbearably dry, yet she still knew what would happen if she tried to speak. Her nearly shattered mind had reached the brink of explosion, just waiting for the slightest trigger.</center>


<center>In a fleeting moment, she remembered that when she had scanned the area before, the seventh corridor had the most knobs. She didn’t know whether that had been an afterimage, even though the white coverage had been so overwhelming. She looked at that damned version of herself, the figure worn down through countless cycles, nearly transparent.</center>


<center>She turned back and returned to the midpoint, the place that could be defined as half darkness. A near-black haze spread out before her, making it impossible to tell which direction led to salvation. Thankfully, the furniture was wedged tightly in place and no longer in her way.</center>


<center>A small dot flashed past her eyes. She stopped, walked toward it, and touched it. A piercing chill surged through her body, the bone-deep cold bringing pain, yet there was no response anymore.</center>


<center>After a few seconds, she pushed open the long wooden door. The once seamless joint had been completely displaced, and the sound it made was unbearable. She looked inside. The unchanging scene continued to present itself, tables, chairs, cabinets, and countless other objects.</center>


<center>She stared blankly ahead, her face devoid of any visible emotion. In truth, emptiness had simply replaced chaos. A nonexistent wind swept through the entire level, and everyone could sense it.</center>


<center>She sprinted again, desperately returning to the very beginning. She knew her end was near, but how could she yield? From the moment she arrived, she should have understood the inevitable conclusion her senses had already recognized.</center>


<center>She kicked hard, and what she saw stunned her. There was suddenly a door inside, not on the wall. It wasn’t new, yet it didn’t belong here. It was... from The Hub.</center>


<center>When the door opened, she lunged forward with all her strength, colliding with someone who had no idea what was happening. Ash-like static blended with naturally visible electromagnetic waves. She opened her eyes.</center>
<br><br>
[[File:ohmyabbr.jpg|400px|center]]
<br><br>
<center>She was alive. As for the other matter, there was no need to concern herself with it anymore, it had already lost all meaning.</center>
